---
import Guide from '../../layouts/Guide.astro';
---
<Guide
  title="How to install SAP Logon Transfer on Windows"
  description="Step-by-step: download and run SAP Logon Transfer on Windows 10 or 11. Free portable tool for SAP Basis admins — no installation, no .NET, no passwords stored."
  keywords="install SAP Logon Transfer, SAP Logon tool Windows, run SAP Logon Transfer, SAP Basis freeware, portable SAP GUI tool"
  path="/guides/install-sap-logon-transfer/"
  tag="Getting started"
  updated="February 2026"
>
  <p>
    SAP Logon Transfer is a <strong>portable</strong> Windows app — there is nothing to
    install and no .NET runtime to set up. You download one file, run it, and you're
    working. This guide walks through it from download to first use.
  </p>

  <figure class="g-figure">
    <img src="/app-screenshot.png" alt="SAP Logon Transfer main window showing folders, systems, SID and server columns" />
    <figcaption>The main window — your systems grouped in folders, ready to export or import.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>What you'll need</h2>
  <ul class="g-checklist">
    <li>Windows 10 (64-bit) or Windows 11</li>
    <li>A couple of minutes — there's no setup wizard</li>
    <li>No admin rights, no .NET, no extra downloads</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step by step</h2>

  <div class="g-steps">
    <div class="g-step">
      <div class="g-step-icon">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M12 3v12m0 0l-4-4m4 4l4-4M5 21h14"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="g-step-body">
        <h3>1. Download the app</h3>
        <p>Head to the <a href="/download/">download page</a> and save the file. It's a
        single, self-contained download — nothing else to fetch.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="g-step">
      <div class="g-step-icon">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><rect x="3" y="4" width="18" height="14" rx="2"/><path d="M9 9l3 2-3 2"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="g-step-body">
        <h3>2. Run it</h3>
        <p>Double-click the app. There's no installer — the window opens directly. If the
        download came as a <code>.zip</code>, extract it first, then run the <code>.exe</code> inside.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="g-step">
      <div class="g-step-icon">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M12 22s8-4 8-10V5l-8-3-8 3v7c0 6 8 10 8 10z"/><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="g-step-body">
        <h3>3. Clear the SmartScreen notice (first launch only)</h3>
        <p>Because the app is new and unsigned, Windows may show a SmartScreen notice.
        Choose <em>More info → Run anyway</em>. The app only reads and writes your own
        SAP connection settings — it never touches the network, the registry, or any
        password store.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="g-step">
      <div class="g-step-icon">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="11" cy="11" r="7"/><path d="M21 21l-4.3-4.3"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="g-step-body">
        <h3>4. Load your systems</h3>
        <p>Click <strong>Auto-detect</strong> and the tool finds the SAP connections on
        your computer. From there you can export folders, import onto another machine,
        share or back up to your cloud folder, or export a report.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <blockquote>
    <strong>Safe by design.</strong> Only connection details are handled — servers,
    routers and system IDs. SAP Logon never stores passwords in these files, and neither
    does the tool. A backup is written before any import.
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Where to next</h2>
  <p>
    Once it's running, the two most common tasks are moving your list to a new machine
    and backing it up before a Windows reinstall:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/guides/move-sap-gui-new-machine/">How to move SAP GUI to a new computer</a></li>
    <li><a href="/guides/backup-sap-gui-settings/">Back up SAP GUI settings before reinstalling Windows</a></li>
  </ul>

  <style>
    .g-figure { margin: 2rem 0; }
    .g-figure img {
      width: 100%; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--line);
      box-shadow: 0 2px 6px rgba(14,26,43,0.06), 0 20px 44px -20px rgba(10,110,209,0.3);
    }
    .g-figure figcaption { margin-top: 0.7rem; font-size: 0.88rem; color: var(--slate-soft); text-align: center; }

    .g-checklist { list-style: none; padding: 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; }
    .g-checklist li { position: relative; padding-left: 1.8rem; }
    .g-checklist li::before {
      content: ""; position: absolute; left: 0; top: 0.55em; width: 12px; height: 7px;
      border-left: 2.5px solid var(--green); border-bottom: 2.5px solid var(--green);
      transform: rotate(-45deg);
    }

    .g-steps { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    .g-step { display: flex; gap: 1rem; align-items: flex-start; background: #fff; border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: var(--radius); padding: 1.2rem 1.4rem; }
    .g-step-icon {
      flex: none; width: 44px; height: 44px; border-radius: 11px;
      background: var(--blue-tint); color: var(--blue);
      display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;
    }
    .g-step-icon svg { width: 22px; height: 22px; }
    .g-step-body h3 { margin: 0.1rem 0 0.3rem; font-size: 1.08rem; }
    .g-step-body p { margin: 0; }
  </style>
</Guide>
